    <fr:title text="Existence and uniqueness of Jordan Canonical Form">Existence and uniqueness of Jordan Canonical Form</fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>theorem</fr:taxon>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
    <html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex> be a <fr:link href="/field-0001/" title="Field" uri="http://localhost:8000/field-0001/" display-uri="field-0001" type="local">Field</fr:link>, let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex> be a positive integer, let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A\in \mathop {\mathrm {Mat}}\nolimits _{n}(\mathbb {F})]]></fr:tex> be an <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\times  n]]></fr:tex> matrix. Assume <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex> contains all the eigenvalues of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>. Then there exists a unique <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\times  n]]></fr:tex> matrix <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathop {\textrm {JCF}}\nolimits (A)]]></fr:tex> called the <html:dfn>Jordan Canonical Form</html:dfn> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> such that the following all hold:</html:p>
    <html:ol><html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A\sim \mathop {\textrm {JCF}}\nolimits (A)]]></fr:tex>;</html:li>
<html:li>For any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B\in \mathop {\mathrm {Mat}}\nolimits _{n}(\mathbb {F})]]></fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A\sim  B]]></fr:tex> if and only if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathop {\textrm {JCF}}\nolimits (A)=\mathop {\textrm {JCF}}\nolimits (B)]]></fr:tex>;</html:li>
<html:li>The <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathop {\textrm {JCF}}\nolimits (A)]]></fr:tex> is a block diagonal matrix consisting of <fr:link href="/ra-005A/" title="Jordan block" uri="http://localhost:8000/ra-005A/" display-uri="ra-005A" type="local">Jordan blocks</fr:link>.</html:li></html:ol>
  </fr:mainmatter>
